The resignations of Nomvuyo Mhlakaza &amp; Aaron Tshidzumba came ahead of the start of a special inquiry. JOHANNESBURG - The presidency says President Jacob Zuma has accepted the resignations of two more South African Broadcasting Corporation (SABC) board members.The resignations of Nomvuyo Mhlakaza and Aaron Tshidzumba came ahead of Tuesday s first meeting of a special Parliamentary committee to inquire the fitness of the SABC board.The resignations of the two board members leaves board chairperson Mbulaheni Maguvhe as the only non-executive member.#SABC President #Zuma has accepted resignations of Ms Vuyo Mhlakaza and Dr Aaron Tshidzumba as board members with immediate effect GDThe multi-party ad hoc committee was appointed by the National Assembly earlier this month and has until the end of February to conclude its work.Tuesday s first meeting is taking place in the wake of reported death threats, harassment and intimidation directed at the SABC 8 who have launched a Constitutional Court challenge against the public broadcaster.Given the threats, the committee is discussing the possibility of providing protection for the witnesses it decides to call.#SABC Even if we have to work over weekends let us do so in best interests of sabc and the country - Chauke GDAfrican national Congress (ANC) Member of Parliament (MP) Vincent Smith has been elected the chairperson of the committee. His election was unopposed. The committee has agreed to begin formal hearings on 29 November and to work over weekends if necessary to conclude the inquiry as quickly as possible.The Presidency's Bongani Ngqulunga says Zuma also wishes the pair well for the future. President Zuma has received and accepted the resignation of Mhlakaza and Tshidzumba. The president also thanked the pair for their contributions during their tenure at the SABC and he has wished them well in all their future endeavours. (Edited by Zamangwane Shange)